 The currents being  \underline{covariant} means that    that under a gauge transformation $(h_R,h_L)$ each current transforms in the adjoint representation of its appropriate   group   
 \begin{eqnarray}
 J_R^\mu &\to& h_R^{-1} J^\mu_R h_{R},\nonumber\\
 J_L^\mu &\to& h_L^{-1} J^\mu_L h_{L}.\nonumber
 \end{eqnarray}
 This property is easily verified.   As a consequence of the transformation properties of the currents their  appropriate covariant derivatives  are 
 \begin{eqnarray}
 \nabla_\mu J^\nu_L= \partial_\mu J^\mu_L +[L_\mu, J^\nu_L],\nonumber\\
 \nabla_\mu J^\nu_R= \partial_\mu J^\mu_R +[R_\mu, J^\nu_R].\nonumber
 \end{eqnarray}

